Based on my reading of RFC 003, the envelope/router/lifecycle code, the network details API, the web hooks, and the multi-agent orchestration / handoff knowledge sources, here is my recommendation:

```json
{
  "recommended_model": {
    "name": "thread-primitive",
    "summary": "Add thread_id as first-class envelope field separate from interaction_id. interaction stays the two-peer work-lifecycle container; thread becomes the conversation-grouping primitive."
  },
  "why_not_the_others": [
    {
      "name": "interaction-becomes-thread",
      "reason": "Drops the two-peer invariant that load-bears lifecycle, receipt routing, and cancellation logic in lifecycle.go and router.go. Larger blast radius for the same UX gain."
    },
    {
      "name": "interaction-becomes-thread",
      "reason": "Conflates work-lifecycle states (submitted/working/needs_input) with conversation grouping. Multi-peer interactions force optional-state semantics that contaminate every state-machine call site."
    },
    {
      "name": "derived-thread-from-reply_to",
      "reason": "Walking reply_to chains is fragile under partial replication, drops, and pagination. Forces UI/store to recompute every render; persistence still needs an index column anyway."
    },
    {
      "name": "thread-only-no-interaction",
      "reason": "Removes the directed-work primitive. Lifecycle has no scope; receipts and traces lose their authoritative two-peer pair. Breaks RFC §3.3 semantics."
    }
